# Common DSW Knowledge Model

Common DSW Knowledge Model deals with questions that a researcher should answer in order to create a Data Stewardship Plan, as well as other related questionnaire data. It originated from mindmap made by Rob Hooft.

## Changelog

Findability
events.description: The Findability metric describes how easily data can be located. The score associated with an answer will be higher if it makes it easier for humans or for computers to locate your data set, e.g. if it ends up in an index or has a unique resolvable identifier.

events.title: Accessibility
events.description: The Accessibility metric describes how well the access to the database is described and how easy it is to implement. The score associated with an answer will be higher if it makes it easier for humans and computers to get to the data. This is determined by e.g. the protocol for accessing the data or for authenticating users, and also by the guaranteed longevity of the repository. Note that this is different from the Openness metric!

events.title: Interoperability
events.description: The Interoperability metric describes how well the data interoperates with other data. The score associated with an answer will be higher if it makes it easier for humans and computers to couple the data with other data and 'understand' relationships. This is influenced by the use of standard ontologies for different fields and proper descriptions of the relations. It is also influenced by proper standard metadata that is agreed by the community.

events.title: Reusability
events.description: The Reusability metric describes how well the data is suitable for reuse in other context. The score associated with an answer will be higher if it makes it easier for humans and computers to reuse the data. This is influenced largely by proper description of how the data was obtained, and also by the conditions that are put on the reuse (license and, for personally identifying information, consent).

events.title: Good DMP Practice
events.description: The Good DMP Practice metric describes how appreciated a process is among Data Stewards. A score associated with an answer will be high if a practice would be considered preferable over alternatives, generally a good idea.

events.title: Openness
events.description: The Openness metric describes how Open the data are available. Note that this is different from the Accessibility metric. A score associated with an answer will be high if the data will be as open as possible, and low if voluntary restrictions apply to access and re-use.

events.text: Before you decide to embark on any new study, it is nowadays good practice to consider all options to keep the data generation part of your study as limited as possible. It is not because we can generate massive amounts of data that we always need to do so. Creating data with public money is bringing with it the responsibility to treat those data well and (if potentially useful) make them available for re-use by others.
events.title: Design of experiment

events.text: Are there any data sets available in the world that are relevant to your planned research?
events.title: Is there any pre-existing data?

events.advice: You know that this is very unlikely? This question is not only about data sets that are similar to what you want to determine yourself, but also reference data or data that should be mined from the existing literature. Further, it is very likely that you will refer to related data, e.g. other databases where you usually "quickly look something up", but that could maybe be properly integrated, especially if you need to do such lookups multiple times.
events.label: No

events.text: Will you be referring to any earlier measured data, reference data, or data that should be mined from existing literature? Your own data as well as data from others?
events.title: Will you be using any pre-existing data (including other people's data)?

events.advice: Did you research all the data that exists? You may not be aware of all existing data that could be available. Although using and/or integrating existing data sets may pose a challenge, it will normally be cheaper than collecting everything yourself. Even if you decide not to use an existing data set, it is better to do this as a conscious decision.
events.label: No

events.text: Much of todays data is used in comparison with reference data. A genome for instance is compared with a reference genome to identify genomic variants. If you use reference data, there are several other issues that you should consider. What are the reference data sets that you will use?
events.title: What reference data will you use?

events.text: Do you know where the reference data is available, what the conditions for use are, and how to reference it?
events.title: Do you know where and how is it available?

events.advice: Figure this out quickly!
events.label: No

events.text: Do you know the data format of the reference data? Is this suitable for your work? Does it need to be converted?
events.title: Do you know in what format the reference data is available?

events.label: I need to convert it before using

events.text: Many reference data sets evolve over time. If the reference data set changes, this may affect your results. If different versions of a reference data set exist, you need to establish your "version policy".
events.title: Is the reference data resource versioned?

events.text: If there are different versions available, you have to decide with all project partners together which version you will be using. Probably you will go for the latest release as of the date of the start of your research project. However, if you have other data from older projects that need to be merged, you may need to consider using the same release you used for a previous project.
events.title: Which version will you use?

events.text: If the reference changes while you are working on your research project, you need to decide whether you will follow these changes. Most likely that will mean that you have to do some analyses again, so you will need to make sure enough resources are available to do so. You can decide to stay with the version that you started with; this can have the disadvantage that you will not benefit from added information or added consistency.
events.title: Will you change version if it updates?

events.label: Will stay with the old version

events.text: Since you want to keep using the old version of the reference data, how will it be available to you?
events.title: How will the old version be available?

events.label: I will need it only at the beginning
I will use a downloaded version
The provider keeps old versions around
New analyses will be done with the new version
All analyses will be redone with the new version

events.text: Will the reference data in the version you use be available to others?
events.title: How will you make sure the same reference data will be available to reproduce your results?

events.label: I will keep a copy and make it available with my results
The provider keeps old versions around

events.text: Even if you will be producing your own data, you often will also be relying on existing data sets (e.g. from earlier . You may need to integrate your new data with an existing data set or retrieve additional information from related data bases. Will you be doing such things?
events.title: What existing non-reference data sets will you use?
Will the owners of this data set work with you on this study
Do you need to request access to the data
Will any usage restrictions affect your reuse?

events.text: If the data that you will re-use is coupled to people, is the informed consent that was originally obtained from those people covering your current research?
events.title: Is extension of any consent for privacy sensitive data needed?
How will you be accessing the data?

events.label: Will download or get a copy

events.text: Do you know the data format of the data? Is this suitable for your work? Does it need to be converted?
events.title: Do you know in what format the data is available?

events.label: I need to convert it before using

events.text: Is the data set you will reuse a fixed data set (with a persistent identifier), or is it a data set that is being worked on (by others) and may be updated during your project or after?
events.title: Is the data set fixed, or will it be updated in the future?

events.label: It is a fixed data set, this will not influence reproducibility of my results

events.advice: Make sure a copy of the version of the input data you use will be available with the results
events.label: It may change

events.text: If you use any filtering, how will you make sure that your results will be reproducible by yourself and others at a later time?
events.title: Can you and will you use the complete existing data set?

events.label: I will use the complete data set
Any filtering or selection will be well documented
I will make sure the selected subset will be available together with my results

events.text: If you are combining data from different sources, harmonization may be required. You may need to re-analyse some original data.
events.title: Do you need to harmonize different sources of existing data?

events.text: By publishing either exactly what you did or (better) make sure that the harmonized data is available for reuse, you may save others the effort
events.title: Will you be making your harmonization results available to others?

events.text: Some old data may need to be recovered, e.g. from tables in scientific papers or may be punch cards.
events.title: Will you be using data that needs to be (re-)made computer readable first?
Will you be making this data available in computer readable form to others?

events.text: Will any of the data that you will be creating form a reference data set for future research (by others)?
events.title: Will reference data be created?

events.text: Who will own the rights to the reference data set? Who will be able to use it?
events.title: What will the Intellectual Property be like?

events.text: How will maintenance be paid for in the long run? Will you host it yourself or deposit it with a repository? How will you deal with requests for help? And with requests for adding data?
events.title: How will you maintain it?

events.text: Will you be updating the reference data at regular intervals?
events.title: How will the release schedule be?
Will you be storing samples?
Will you be collecting experimental data?

events.text: In the data design and planning phase, we will make sure that we know what data comes when, that we have enough storage space and compute power to deal with it, and that all the responsibilities have been taken care of.
events.title: Data design and planning

events.text: Have you identified types of data that you will use that are used by others too? Some types of data (e.g. genetic variants in the life sciences) are used by many different projects. For such data, often common standards exist that help to make these data reusable. Are you using such common data formats?
events.title: What data formats/types will you be using?
Is this a standard data format used by others too?

events.text: Complicated (binary) file formats tend to change over time, and software may not stay compatible with older versions. Also, some formats hamper long term usability by making use of patents or being hampered by restrictive licensing
events.title: Does this data format enable sharing and long term archiving?
Will you convert to a file format more suitable for archiving later?

events.advice: You may need to reserve time and budget for this
events.label: Yes

events.text: Sometimes the type of data you collect can not be stored in a commonly used data format. In such cases you may need to make your own, keeping interoperability as high as possible.
events.title: Will you be using new types of data?

events.label: No, all of my data will fit in common formats
Yes, I will need to use custom formats for some of my data

events.text: Even if the data format you are using is unique to your project, the discrete data items should be reused or reusable as much as possible. Data type registries can help with that.
events.title: Will you need to add fields in your data format to a data type registry?

events.label: No, all of my data types are described in a data type registry already
Yes, I will add new types to an existing data type registry
Yes, I will create my own data type registry

events.title: Which data type registries will you use?

events.text: For good interoperability the use of controlled vocabularies for each discrete data item is advisable. If such vocabularies exist, it is best to reuse those.
events.title: Do you need to create vocabularies or ontologies for any of your data items?

events.label: No, suitable public controlled vocabularies or ontologies exist for all of my data types
Yes, I will make and publish a vocabulary or ontology for some of my data

events.title: How will you design your new data format?

events.label: There is a closely related more generic and open format that I can specialize
I will use a Linked Data format
I will use a completely custom data format

events.title: Will you describe your new data format for others?

events.label: Yes, I will register my standards at a data standards registry

events.text: For the re-usability of your data by yourself or others at a later stage, a lot of information about the data, how it was collected and how it can be used should be stored with the data. Such data about the data is called metadata, and this set of questions are about this metadata
events.title: How will you be storing metadata?
Do suitable 'Minimal Metadata About ...' (MIA...) standards exist for your experiments?

events.advice: Did you really check a service like fairsharing.org to verify this?
events.label: No

events.title: Do you have a good idea of what metadata is needed to make it possible for others to read and interpret your data in the future?

events.text: Often it is easiest to make sure you collect the metadata as early as possible.
events.title: Do you know how and when you will be collecting the necessary metadata?

events.text: Adding more than the strict minimum metadata about your experiment will possibly allow more wide re-use of your data, with associated higher data citation rates. Please note that it is not easy for yourself to see all other ways in which others could be reusing your data.
events.title: Will you consider re-usability of your data beyond your original purpose?

events.label: No, I will just document the bare minimum
Yes, I will document more metadata than needed for reproducibility

events.title: How will you balance the extra efforts with the potential for added reusability?

events.label: I will see what I can do
I will use preselected additional standard modules of metadata
I will collect all metadata I can gather and document the data set beyond minimal standards

events.title: Do you need to exchange your data with others?

events.text: Working with large amounts of heterogenous data in a larger research group has implications for the data integrity. How do you make sure every step of the workflow is done with the right version of the data? How do you handle the situation when a mistake is uncovered? Will you be able to redo the strict minimum data handling?
events.title: Did you consider how to monitor data integrity?

events.text: Data corruption or mistakes can happen with large amounts of files or large files. Keeping a master list with data checksums can be helpful to prevent expensive mistakes. It can also be helpful to keep the sample list under version control forcing that all changes are well documented.
events.title: Will you be keeping a master list with checksums of certified/correct/canonical/verified data?
Will you define a way to detect file or sample swaps, e.g. by measuring something independently?

events.text: It is not always clear to everyone in the project (ad outside) what can and can not be done with a data set. It is helpful to associate each data set with a license as early as possible in the project. A data license should ideally be as free as possible: any restriction like 'only for non-commercial use' or 'attribution required' may reduce the reusability and thereby the number of citations. If possible, use a computer-readable and computer actionable license.
events.title: Do all datasets you work with have a license?

events.text: It is very likely that data will be moved and copied. At some point people may lose track of the origins. It can be helpful to have the licenses (of coarse as open as possible) stored in close association with the data.
events.title: Will you store the licenses with the data at all time?

events.text: To make your experiments reproducible, all steps in the data processing must be documented in detail. The software you used, including version number, all options and parameters. This information together for every step of the analysis is part of the so-called data provenance. There are more questions regarding this in the chapter on data processing and curation.
events.title: How will you keep provenance?

events.description: Keeping a log of every step in the analysis workflow that has been run

events.label: All steps will be documented in an (electronic) lab notebook
Our work flow system documents the provenance automatically and completely

events.text: Putting some thoughts into file naming can save a lot of trouble later.
events.title: How will you do file naming and file organization?

events.text: It can help if everyone in the project uses the same naming scheme.
events.title: Did you make a SOP (Standard Operating Procedure) for file naming?

events.text: Advice: Use the same identifiers for sample IDs etc throughout the entire project.
events.title: Will you be keeping the relationships between data clear in the file names?

events.text: The file names are very useful as metadata for people involved in the project, but to computers they are just identifiers. To prevent accidents with e.g. renamed files metadata information should always also be available elsewhere and not only through the file name.
events.title: Will all the metadata in the file names also be available in the proper metadata?

events.label: No, the file names in the project are an essential part of the metadata
Yes, all metadata is also explicitly available elsewhere

events.text: Much of the raw data you have will need to be archived for your own later use somewhere. This is often done off-line on tape, not on the disks of the compute facility. Please note that this does not refer to the data publication.
events.title: During the project, will you be archiving data (using so-called 'cold storage') for long term preservation?

events.description: Archiving data when the project is finished

events.title: Can the original data be regenerated?
When is the raw data archived?

events.description: Archiving raw data from the working area

events.label: As soon as it comes in, in chunks
As soon as it has all arrived, in one session
All at once with the results at the end of the project

events.title: Is the archived data changing over time, needing re-archival?

events.text: The general term 'backup' is used for protection against two different kinds of problems: equipment failure and human error. Protections against these two may need different solutions. Both are considered backup for this and subsequent questions.
events.title: Do you need frequent backups?
Will you be relying on these backups to recover from human error (accidental changes or deletions)?

events.advice: This puts other demands on the possibility to restore files. Make sure this is covered
events.label: Yes

events.title: Will the archive be stored on disk or on tape?
Will the archive be stored in a remote location, protecting the data against disasters?
Will the archive need to be protected against loss or theft?
Will the archive be encrypted?

events.label: No, the data does not need protection

events.title: Is it clear who has access to the key? Also in case of a required data restore?
Is it clear who has physical access to the archives?
Will your project require the archives to be available on-line?

events.text: If the 'master copy' of the data is available on line, it should probably be protected against being tampered with.
events.title: Will data integrity be guaranteed?
Is there an interface and a defined process for people to request access to the data?
Has it been established who has access to the archive, and how fast?
Has it been established who can ask for a restore during the project?
If the data is voluminous, will the project be able to cope with the time needed for a restore?
Has authority over the data been arranged for when the project is finished (potentially long ago)? Is there a data access committee?
Has it been established how long the archived data need to be kept? For each of the different parts of the archive (raw data / results)?

events.text: See also all questions about keeping metadata and data formats. Make sure the metadata is kept close to the data in the archive, and that community supported data formats are used for all long term archiving.
events.title: Will the data still be understandable after a long time?
Will you need a shared working space to work with your data?
Are data all project members store adequately backed up and traceable?

events.label: Yes, protected against both equipment failure and human error

events.text: There are several questions regarding the dynamics of the data in the working area, who works with it, the software that is run on it, etc.
events.title: How will you work with your data?

events.text: When making the work space, it helps to know whether you expect to work with very many small files, a few very large files, whether you will use a (SQL) database to store most of the data. Maybe your data is suitable for a system like Hadoop? Such information can be collected here.
events.title: What kind of data will you have in your work space?

events.text: If you have large volumes of data that are intensely and repeatedly used by the computing work flow, it may be needed to keep the storage in the same place as where the computing takes place.
events.title: Do you need the work space to be close to the compute capacity?

events.text: Archival and working with data have different requirements. You want archived information to be in a form that others could read and in a format that is also understandable in a number of years. When working with the data, you need to be able to address it efficiently. If the two differ, you need to plan for conversions.
events.title: Will you be working with your data in another form than the way it will be archived?

events.label: No, data format will be archived in the same way we work with it
Yes, archival will require a conversion step

events.text: To perform capacity planning, it is important to know what the need for storage capacity at the beginning and the end of the project will be.
events.title: How does the storage need change over time?

events.label: Storage needs will be the same during the whole project
Storage needs are large at the beginning and will be reduced later
Storage needs are small at the beginning and will grow later
Storage needs are largest in the middle of the project

events.title: When will your raw data become available?

events.label: Raw data will come in right at the start
Raw data will come in during the project

events.text: Sometimes the raw data is relatively large, and it pays of to clean it quickly.
events.title: How much of the raw data do you need to keep in the work space?

events.label: Raw data will need to stay in the work space
Raw data can be cleaned out or archived quickly

events.title: Do your raw data need to be archived?

events.label: No, it is also stored elsewhere can be recovered easily
No, it can be remeasured easily and more cheaply than archiving
Raw data do not form a major part of the storage needs
Raw data will only be loaded in the work space on demand from the primary archives

events.title: Did you plan how much intermediate data you will get during analysis and how long each step needs to be kept?

events.label: The volume of intermediate data will not be significant
A large volume of intermediate data will be in the work space

events.text: If the intermediate results are in your main work space, a restore in case of a problem could take much more time. It may be faster to recover it by re-running computations
events.title: Is it possible to store intermediate temporary data on a separate (scratch) area that is not backed up?

events.label: We will use the main work space for temporary data
We can offload intermediate results to a scratch area that is not backed up

events.title: Are you sure you will not need a backup of the data stored on the scratch file systems (any scratch you use)?

events.label: How CSC restored 850 million temporary files

events.text: Consider storing only the workflow parameters if the data itself could be reproduced quickly
events.title: Will you have different versions of intermediate data that need to be kept?

events.text: Usually, data sets will be archived if it is unlikely you need them in the short term, but it would be hard to create them again, and/or they are essential for reproducing your work. Archival storage of large volumes can be significantly cheaper than keeping it in the working area for an extensive period.
events.title: Will you need to temporarily archive data sets (e.g. to tape)?
How will your first data come in?

events.label: No special planning is needed for the initial data
Initial data will need to be made available through a local network copy
We will need a high-speed network connection to copy the initial data
Initial data will arrive on separate media and will need to be copied to the work space

events.title: How will project partners access the work space?
Who will arrange access control?

events.label: Project management will need to be able to give people access
The work space should be connected to a single-sign-on system

events.title: Will the work space storage need to be remote mounted?

events.label: No, data will be copied if it needs to be processed elsewhere
No, all data processing will be done in the same environment (virtual research environment)
Yes, for actual computations, requiring high performance

events.title: Will data be copied out and in to the workspace storage by remote users?

events.description: Workflow that is split over multiple work locations

events.label: No, this should not be allowed
No, all data processing will be done in the same environment (virtual research environment)
Yes, for actual computations, requiring high performance

events.title: Are data integrity and reliability requirements also met by the other storage spaces used in the project?

events.text: There are a number of questions that can help you to decide whether your work space will be reliable enough for your project.
events.title: How available/reliable should must the work space be?
What is the acceptable risk for a total loss?

events.label: All essential data is also stored elsewhere

events.title: Is there software in the work space? Can it also be restored quickly?

events.label: Software in the work space is only a copy
Special care will be taken for the software and configurations

events.title: Can you handle it when the work space is off line for a while?

events.label: We could handle a few days of offline time per year
We can only miss the work space for a few hours during work hours
Problems during the evenings and weekends can not wait for work hours to be repaired

events.title: How long can you wait for a restore if the storage fails?

events.label: We can wait for repair and a restore
A spare copy needs to be deployed quickly
No waiting is possible, a hot copy must be ready to take over

events.title: How long can you wait for a restore if you accidentally damage a file?

events.label: Any user needs to be able to restore an old copy instantaneously

events.text: Are there any data files e.g. on laptops of project members? Also: supercomputing centers and other high performance computer centers often write in their terms of use that you need to take care of your own backups
events.title: Will you make backup copies of project data that is not in the work space?

events.label: This is left to the project participants
All data elsewhere is adequately backed up
We make (automated) backups of all data stored outside of the working area

events.text: There are many factors that can contribute to the risk of information loss or information leaks. They are often part of the behavior of the people that are involved in the project, but can also be steered by properly planned infrastructure.
events.title: Is the risk of information loss, leaks and vandalism acceptably low?

events.text: When assessing the risk, take into account who has access to the lab, who has (physical) access to the computer hardware itself. Also consider whether data on those systems is properly backed up
events.title: Do project members store data or software on computers in the lab or external hard drives connected to those computers?

events.text: Does anyone carry project data on laptops, USB sticks or other external media?
events.title: Do project members carry data with them?
Are all data carriers encrypted? Are accounts on the laptop password protected?

events.text: Think about services like Dropbox, but also about Google Drive, Apple iCloud accounts, or Microsoft's Office365
events.title: Do project members store project data in cloud accounts?
Do project members send project data or reports per e-mail or other messaging services?
Do all data centers where project data is stored carry sufficient certifications?
Are all project web services addressed via secure http (https://)?

events.text: Project members may need to know about passwords (not sharing accounts, using different passwords for each service, and two factor authentication), about security for data they carry (encryption, backups), data stored in their own labs and in personal cloud accounts, and about the use of open WiFi and https
events.title: Have project members been instructed about the risks (generic and specific to the project)?
Did you consider the possible impact to the project or organization if information is lost?

events.label: Yes; the risk is acceptably low
Yes; we will need to work on this.

events.title: Did you consider the possible impact to the project or organization if information leaks?

events.label: Yes; the risk is acceptably low
Yes; we will need to work on this.

events.label: Yes; the risk is acceptably low

events.text: If you require substantial amounts of compute power, amounts that are not trivially absorbed in what you usually have abailable, some planning is necessary. Do you think you need to do compute capacity planning?
events.title: Do you need to do compute capacity planning?

events.text: Did you run pilot jobs? Do you know this information from comparable projects? Did you test whether the work scales up as you expected if you run more than one job?

# Common DSW Knowledge Model

Common DSW Knowledge Model deals with questions that a researcher should answer in order to create a Data Stewardship Plan, as well as other related questionnaire data. It originated from mindmap made by Rob Hooft.

text.value: Roles in a project should be given as they are defined by [datacite](https://schema.datacite.org/meta/kernel-4.1/doc/DataCite-MetadataKernel_v4.1.pdf). You should specify at least one "Contact Person".

Much of todays data is used in comparison with reference data. You may be comparing your own data with a "standard set" which is maintained as a collection by someone else. Or you could be determining differences to a stanndard (in bioinformatics, a genome is often compared with a reference genome to identify genomic variants). If you use reference data, there are several other issues that you should consider. What are the reference data sets that you will use?

Before you decide to embark on any new study, it is nowadays good practice to check all options to re-use existing available data, either collected or generated by yourself in an earlier project, or data from others (Barend Mons calls this "Other PEople's Data And Services" or OPEDAS). This can include reusable data that have been created for an earlier study, and also so-called "reference data" which is used by many projects.

It is not because we can generate massive amounts of data that we always need to do so. Creating data with public money is bringing with it the responsibility to treat those data well and (if potentially useful) make them available for re-use by others. And the circle is only complete if such data is actually re-used.

We will make sure that we know what data will be coming together in the project, when it will be coming. We also need to make sure that we have adequate storage space to deal with it, and that all the responsibilities have been taken care of.

Have you identified types of data that you will use that are used by others too? Some types of data (for example "images" or "tables") are used by many different projects. For such data, often common standards exist (in our example "JPG" and "CSV") that help to make these data reusable. Are you using such common data formats?

Complicated (binary) file formats tend to change over time, and software may not stay compatible with older versions. Also, some formats hamper long term usability by making use of patents or being hampered by restrictive licensing.

Even if you will be producing your own data, you often will also be relying on existing data sets (e.g. from your own earlier projects). You may need to integrate your new data with an existing data set or retrieve additional information from related data bases. Will you be doing such things?
Give a name for the data set. You will get suggestions listing databases listed in FAIRSharing, but you can also specify data sets that are not listed.
There can be restrictions imposed on the re-use of data. This could be through licensing, or if personal or sensitive data is involved there may be other restrictions (e.g. consent).

If the data that you will re-use is coupled to people, the informed consent that was originally obtained from those people may not be covering your current research. In that case re-consent may be necessary.
Will you be using a working space that is shared between all the people working on the data in the project? Sometimes such a system is called a *Virtual Research Environment*.
Each person contributing to creating or executing the data management plan should be added as a contributor. A project probably should have a Contact Person, and a Data Curator.

Roles in a project should be given as they are defined by [datacite](https://schema.datacite.org/meta/kernel-4.1/doc/DataCite-MetadataKernel_v4.1.pdf). 

You should specify at least one "Contact Person". If your project has a work package for data management, identify the leader of that work package as "Data Curator".

# Common DSW Knowledge Model

Common DSW Knowledge Model deals with questions that a researcher should answer in order to create a Data Stewardship Plan, as well as other related questionnaire data. It originated from mindmap made by Rob Hooft.

### 2.0.1

* Fixed duplicated question in *Creating and collecting data* chapter (5ba53879-eb48-47f2-a73b-f7f7d83bf030)

* Added administrative chapter

### 1.4.0

Before you decide to embark on any new study, it is good practice to check all options to re-use existing available data, either collected or generated by yourself in an earlier project, or data from others (Barend Mons calls this "Other PEople's Data And Services" or OPEDAS). This can include reusable data that have been created for an earlier study, and also so-called "reference data" which is used by many projects.

It is not because we can generate massive amounts of data that we always need to do so. Creating data with public money is bringing with it the responsibility to treat those data well and (if potentially useful) make them available for re-use by others. And the circle is only complete if such data is actually re-used.

advice.value: It is possible that you have overlooked existing data! This question is not only about data sets that are similar to what you want to determine yourself, but also reference data or data that should be mined from the existing literature. Further, it is very likely that you will refer to related data, e.g. other databases where you usually "quickly look something up", but that could maybe be properly integrated, especially if you need to do such lookups multiple times.

text.value: Many research fields have worked together to define what kind of metadata should really be collected when an experiment of a certain kind is performed and described. That information is described in a Minimal Metadata Standard. Often, these standards describe both what kind of information needs to be collected as well as the format in which it is expected.

Have you identified types of data that you will use that are used by others too? Some types of data (for example "images" or "tables") are used by many different projects. For such data, often common standards exist (in our example "JPG" and "CSV") that help to make these data reusable. Are you using such common data formats?

Please make sure you list all the data types that are important for your project. You should make sure also to list the formats used in any data sets that you are re-using.

events.text: Formats like XLS or SQL are very flexible; they can be adapted to many different uses, and this makes them good for interoperability. However, their flexibility also makes that it is not immediately obvious from the file structure how it can be used. The data needs a proper *description* in order for others (or yourself at a later time) to be able to unambiguously understand what it contains.

There are many kinds of metadata, each serving their own purpose.  Some key metadata that you should consider:
* There is metadata that helps identify where the data is coming from (e.g. who created it, title). For this the Dublin Core is often used.
* There are different ways of adding metadata to make the data "discoverable" for other researchers. This requires either keywords or ontology terms describing what is in the data.
* There is metadata describing how the data can be re-used, such as license information and, for data about people, the extent of their consent for data reuse.
* There is metadata describing where the data comes from and what it is useful for. For frequently used data types, there are often very well defined metadata standards, in other cases you may need to think about this yourself.

* There is metadata describing how the data can be re-used, such as license information and, for data about people, the extent of their consent for data reuse.
* There is metadata that makes the data understandable, e.g. linking to the exact processes used to collect them (is a *body temperature* measured under the tongue or in the rectum?) and units (is a temperature given in Celsius or Fahrenheit?). 
* There is metadata describing where the data comes from and what it is useful for. For frequently used data types, there are often very well defined metadata standards, in other cases you may need to think about this yourself.
For each of these kinds of metadata there are specific standards. There is no single standard that will get you all the metadata needed to make the data as FAIR as possible.

events.text: The term "distribution" used here is as defined by the very widely used W3C DCAT metadata application profile. It is used to mean a particular instance of a dataset that has been, or is intended to be, made available in some fashion. It is important to separate the logical notion of a "dataset" from its distributions, of which there may be several, especially to attach more specific metadata properties such as "size" and "license". The lifecycle of the DMP has no particular bearing on this, and a "distribution" may be defined even if the DMP is never actually realised.
